f his first wife, Keziah","related_id":"X00113","link_text":"Rev. Edward Taylor"}],"gender":"male","tags":["slaveholder"],"number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Rev., Hooker descendant"},"bio":{"title":"Reverend","display_name":"Rev. Isaac Stiles","first_name":"Isaac","last_name":"Stiles","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1722"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"education":[{"school_name":"Yale College","dates":"1722","type":"undergraduate"},{"school_name":"Yale College","dates":"1726","type":"graduate","notes":"A.M."}],"career":[{"role":"Pastor","organization":"Church of Christ, North Haven","start_year":1724,"end_year":1760}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"religion","header":"Thirty-six years in North Haven’s pulpit","body":"Yale 1722, Stiles held the North Haven pastorate for thirty-six years and raised — by his first wife — Ezra Stiles, the Enlightenment polymath who became Yale’s seventh president. His Hooker-descended children came by his second wife, Esther Hooker."},{"number":2,"category":"religion","header":"He preached against his own melon thief","body":"Spotting a parishioner stealing his melons during the Sunday intermission, Stiles named him from the afternoon pulpit: “I saw you, John Johnson, thou son of Belial… enter my garden and steal my melons.” His son Ezra called it “rather close preaching, but characteristic of the times.”"},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"His first wife was the poet’s daughter","body":"Keziah Taylor, daughter of the metaphysical poet Rev. Edward Taylor of Westfield, died in childbed in December 1727 — twenty-five years old, two years married. Within the year Stiles remarried, to Esther Hooker of Farmington, who bore his ten North Haven children."},{"number":4,"category":"religion","header":"First of his blood liberally educated","body":"Yale 1722 — “the first of the name and blood that had a liberal education in America” — he published “A Looking-glass for Changlings” against political turncoats in 1743. His son Ezra became president of the college; his epitaph fills a monument at North Haven."}],"slug":"isaac-stiles-1697"},"H00092":{"id":"H00092","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":4,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1702,"month":11,"day":30,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00028","mother_id":"I00056"},"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 92"}],"death":{"year":1779,"month":1,"day":2,"city":"North Haven","state":"Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00126","children_ids":["H00238","H00239","H00240","H00241","H00242","H00243","H00244","H00245","H00246","H00247"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1728,"date_month":10}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"HD1459","display_label":"Esther Hooker Stiles was the great-grandmother of Horace Stiles who.","link_text":"Levinia Pierpont Stiles"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"H00882","display_label":"Esther Hooker Stiles was the great-grandmother of Horace Stiles who.","link_text":"Benjamin Pierpont Jr."}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Esther Hooker Stiles","first_name":"Esther","last_name":"Stiles","married_names":["Stiles"],"maiden_name":"Hooker"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Second wife of Rev. Isaac Stiles","body":"She married Rev. Isaac Stiles of North Haven as his second wife. His first wife Keziah Taylor — daughter of the great Puritan poet Rev. Edward Taylor — had died in childbirth on December 4, 1727."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Raised Ezra Stiles, future Yale president","body":"She raised her stepson Ezra Stiles from infancy after his birth mother Keziah Taylor's death. He became President of Yale (1778-1795) and one of the most important intellectuals of the American Founding."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Ten children with Stiles between 1729 and 1750","body":"She and Isaac Stiles had ten children of their own between 1729 and 1750. Only Ezra was Keziah's son from the first marriage; all others were Esther's, carrying the Stiles-Hooker line forward through North Haven."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Her name traveled five generations as Esther Hooker","body":"The name 'Esther Hooker' became a heritable token across five generations of Stiles women — from her (1702) to her granddaughter (1760), and onward through Alice Stiles Mills (1845). Her name carried farther than her lineage."}],"slug":"esther-stiles-1702"},"H00028":{"id":"H00028","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":3,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1661,"month":5,"day":29,"city":"Plymouth","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1730,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00007","mother_id":"I00006"},"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 28"},{"short":"Native Northeast Portal","url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-samuel-jr","notes":"Samuel Hooker Jr. biography; confirms Plymouth birth, Hartford merchant activity"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00056","children_ids":["H00086","H00087","H00088","H00089","H00090","H00091","H00092","H00093"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1687,"date_month":6,"date_day":28,"location_city":"Farmington","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"gender":"male","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM043","landmark_blurb":"His father lived here, directly opposite the Giles Hooker house on Main Street."}],"residence":{"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Born in Plymouth in his father's transition year","body":"He was born in Plymouth, Massachusetts on May 29, 1661 — where his father Rev. Samuel Hooker had been preaching for several years. The family moved to Farmington that same year, where his father succeeded his brother-in-law Roger Newton as minister."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"His house stood south of the burial ground","body":"Samuel Hooker II had a fine residence at Farmington, next south of the old burial ground — later known as the Mix house — and ran a store for mercantile business in Hartford. He was one of the first of the Farmington Hookers to move from ministry into trade."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"He married a wealthy sea captain's daughter","body":"In 1687 Samuel Hooker married Mehitabel Hamlin of Middletown, daughter of Capt. Giles Hamlin, a noted and wealthy sea captain and merchant. Hooker kept a store and traded out of Hartford while living at Farmington."}],"cross_connections":[],"career":[{"role":"Merchant","organization":"Farmington / Hartford","notes":"Mercantile business. Store and fine residence at Farmington."}],"education":[{"degree":"B.A.","notes":"B.A. Harvard; later a fellow of the college. (Julius Gay, Farmington Historical Pamphlets)","school_name":"Harvard College","institution_id":"INST002"}